The following example results are from the 2022 Spanish Grand Prix.

You should follow the same process and show the same results, but for the 2022 Dutch Grand Prix

Calculating Cumulative Lap times¶

In order to evaluate race strategy (including tyre and pit stop strategy) we need to know the relative position of each driver as the race progresses. We can derive this from the lap times of each driver. We start by calculating the cumulative lap time for each driver lap by lap. The cumulative lap time after the first lap will be the lap time for the first lap; the cumulative lap time at the end of the second lap will be the sum of the lap times for the first two laps and so on.

Start by creating a Python function to compute the cummulative lap time for a given driver at a given lap. The function will take as a parameter a single row from your Pandas data frame containing the lap data. This row will include the Driver and the LapNumber. Your function should return a floating point number representing the cummulative lap time for that driver up to the end of that lap in the race.

You can then apply that function to each row in your Pandas data frame to compute a new column representing the cummulative lap time (see example below).

Calculate Driver Position relative to other drivers¶

If at the end of lap N, driver A's cummulative lap time is less than driver B's cummulative lap time then we can conclude that driver A is ahead of driver B at that point in the race. Our next goals is to therefore compute the position of each driver at the end of each lap based on their cumulative lap times.

Start by creating a Python function to compute the relative position for a given driver at a given lap. The function will take as a parameter a single row from your Pandas data frame containing the lap data. This row will contain the Driver, the LapNumber and the CumulativeLapTime. Your function should return an integer number representing the relative position of that driver up to that point in the race. The driver at the head of the race will have a position of 1, the next driver will have a position of 2 and so on.

You can then apply that function to each row in your Pandas data frame to compute a new column named Position (see example below).

Join with previous lap for that driver¶

To determine overtakes and other important statistics we need to combine data for a particular lap (for a particular driver) with the data for the previous lap for that same driver.

First we need to know which row in the data frame corresponds to the previous lap for the same driver.

Start by creating a Python function to compute the index of the row that corresponds to the previous lap for a given driver at a given lap. The function will take as a parameter a single row from your Pandas data frame containing the lap data. This row will contain the Driver and the LapNumber. Your function should return an integer number representing the index of the row that contains the same driver but on the previous lap (LapNumber-1). If no such row exists (for example for the first lap) then your function should instead return NaN (Not a Number).

You can then apply that function to each row in your Pandas data frame to compute a new column named PreviousIndex (see example below).

Compute Pit stop durations based on joined lap data¶

We can now use this joined lap data to compute the duration of each pit stop. Note this is not the time spent stationary (typically around 3 seconds), but the entire time from when they entered the pit lane until they leave the pit lane (typically around 20 seconds).

To compute the pit stop time we calculate the difference between when they enter the pit lane (as part of the previous lap) and when they exist the pit lane (as part of the next lap).

Compute Overtakes based on joined lap data¶

Next we can use the joined lap data to help calculate when a driver overtook another driver. We say that driver A overtook driver B on lap N if driver A was behind driver B on the previous lap (N-1) but was then ahead of driver B by the end of the next lap (N).

Start by creating a Python function to compute the drivers that were overtaken by a particular driver on a particular lap. The function will take as a parameter a single row from your joined lap data frame (containing the lap data from both the previous and current lap). This row will contain the Driver, LapNumber, current Position and Position_previous (from the previous lap). Your function should return the Drivers from rows of the joined lap data that match the LapNumber and such that the driver was behind in the previous lap but ahead in the next lap.

You can then use a for loop to iterate through the rows of the joined lap data frame (sorted by LapNumber and then driver Position) and call the overtakes function to determine which if any drivers were overtaken by that driver on that lap. For those cases where there was an overtake, print out the names of both drivers involved and the lap number on which it occurred. Note that a driver may overtake more than one other driver per lap.

Challenge Question: The Undercut¶

The following is a challenge exercise. It is designed to identify outstanding levels of achievement (i.e. for those students aiming to achieve a grade of 7).

You can skip it if you are not seeking such a challenge.

You can find plenty of information on the web around the race/pitstop strategy referred to as "Undercutting".

  • https://f1chronicle.com/how-the-undercut-works-in-f1/
  • https://au.motorsport.com/f1/news/f1-strategy-explained-whats-an-undercut-overcut-a-drs-train-and-more/10500436/
  • https://thesportsrush.com/f1-news-undercut-f1-what-is-the-meaning-of-undercut-in-formula-1-complete-explanation/

If a driver is stuck behind a driver immediately ahead and is unable to get past then on the track, they can instead use a different tactic to get ahead of their opponent. The strategy involves coming in for a pit stop in some lap before their opponent. The pit stops takes around 20 seconds to complete, so by the time that car returns to the track they will be way behind their opponent. However, if they time it well, they will come back out onto the track in "free air" (i.e. without another driver directly ahead). They will then be able to exploit their fresh new tires and go as fast as the car is able without being slowed down by a car immediately in front. They will therefore hopefully close the gap on their original opponent ahead such that when their opponent eventually also takes their pit stop (normally one or two laps latter), by the time they reenter the track, we can get ahead of them.

Based on the data we have available, how might you identify when an undercut has occurred?
